Comment:
Please don‚Äôt. It is not one of those movies, like The Room or any Adam Sandler movie, that is so embarrassingly bad that it becomes funny or watchable. Its bad in a different way, in a way that makes you want to gouge your eyes out with a spoon. 

Having been dumb enough to see this in the cinema when it came out, I can say that this is, without a doubt, the most terrible movie I have ever seen or that I believe has ever existed. It is a criminally shameless cash grab that was created with the sole intention of stealing money from the pockets of unsuspecting movie goers. At least other terrible movies produce some sort of enjoyment due to the fact that they are so bad... However, there was not a single second of this movie that involved something of merit, enjoyment or anything that resembled comedy in any way. It was clearly created without an inch of effort, and feels as though it was written within the space of an hour and filmed in the space of a day. Everyone involved in the creation of this movie should be absolutely completely and utterly ashamed that they were involved in such a horrifically disgusting abomination. Please, I beg of you, no one buy this movie on any streaming service or on blue ray/DVD. You will be giving your hard earned money to literal scam artists - this movie is literally a scam in itself.

Comment:
You forgot Jeremy Brett and David Burke.  They are British actors that made a series of ALL the books of Sherlock Holmes and Watson... 
"The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes (1984‚Äì1985), The Return of Sherlock Holmes (1986‚Äì1988), The Case-Book of Sherlock Holmes (1991‚Äì1993) and The Memoirs of Sherlock Holmes (1994), collectively known as Sherlock Holmes, are a series of adaptations of Arthur Conan Doyle's Sherlock Holmes stories which were produced by Granada Television and originally broadcast by ITV in the United Kingdom. The series starred Jeremy Brett as Holmes and David Burke (in the Adventures series) and Edward Hardwicke (Return, Case-Book, Memoirs) as Dr. Watson."  

If you are a Holmes and Watson fan, these are a must see.  Jeremy Brett (now deceased) was awesome as Holmes.  These episodes are based on each one of the stories as written by Arthur Conan Doyle and done with the quality you expect for a British production.  And yes there was a parody with Michael Caine and Ben Kingsley called "Without a clue" that was really funny.  It came out in 1988.

Comment: Md.Nazmul Alam Evan the 20th century was 1900 to 1999. Sherlock Holmes time period is 1875 to 1920. Judging by the ship design, the movie takes place post 1890. Or it could just be an anarchism for comedic effect.
author: @1981deloreanfan

Comment:
@Md.Nazmul Alam Evan "The SS Great Eastern, launched on 31 January 1858 (a full 40 years ahead of any comparable ships), was the only ocean liner to sport five funnels. As one funnel was later removed, the Great Eastern, by default, became the first ocean liner to have four funnels. However, after the Great Eastern became a four funnel ship she never carried passengers so really should not be considered the first four funnel liner. The SS Kaiser Wilhelm der Grosse, launched on 4 May 1897, was properly the first ocean liner to have four funnels and was one of the first of the golden era of ocean liners that became prominent in the early- to mid-20th century." (Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four_funnel_liner).

The adventures of Holmes and Watson take place between 1880 and 1914 (source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sherlock_Holmes), however, since queen Victoria died in 1901, the ship in the trailer could be one of three early four-funnel ships. However, after a quick comparison with some of the images of the early four-funnel ships (source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four_funnel_liner), it appears as though this is indeed a good ol' anachronism, as 1981deloranfan pointed out, since this ship is indeed one of the Olympic class liners owned by the White Star Line, as apparent by the color of the funnels (known as "White Star Buff"). Why they chose to do this? I guess we'll have to wait until the movie is out to know.

Comment: ¬†@matthewthurber3807¬† Yea I get they have to physically find them, but the entire thing about Sherlock is that you don't know who committed the murder til the very end, that's what made it such  a good series as you went through the pacing of how they figure it out. You see this is many detective novels or films, because it builds suspension and over time it has evolved into the key element of a detective novels or film. It's what brings the mystery alive. I understand there is a lot about this film that is highly different to the books or TV show that came out on the BBC, but to take the mystery away from the detective genre, there is no suspension. Sherlock is famous for bringing the reader (or watcher in case of the other films and TV show) through the journey with the characters, sometimes allowing you to figure out the murderer before they do which gives you a sense of achievement of satisfaction. To tell you in the trailer who did it just makes it less Sherlock in my  opinion, yes they still have to find the person, but they have missed a key element out that all the other Sherlock's have had over the years.
author: @leomp7269
